Phase XII: Use levels, robbing and abandonments continue.

The soil deposit overlying the uppermost preserved architectural features. It includes both the overburden and the sediment strata, as it was not possible to distinguish between them during the excavation process due to a high degree of post-sedimentation disturbance in the area, including the recent deposition of ashy soil during the excavation of Tr. 127.The deposit of fine, compacted soil included materials of varying sizes: clay, silt, sand, and cobbles. Fairly homogenous in nature, the Munsell Color range was predominantly between 10 YR 4/1 (Dark Gray) and 10YR 3/1 (Very Dark Gray), indicating a high percentage of ash distributed through the deposit; some pockets of 7.5 YR 5/4 (Brown) were evident throughout as well. The locus contained many architectural fragments including wall, door, floor, roof, and hypocaust system elements. While most of these materials were deposited as a result of a collapse event, the soil deposit in and around these elements appears to have been the result of natural sedimentation processes. The deposit did yield pottery, bone, shell, glass, metal, and vegetal matter, as well as many pieces of marble/opus sectile thought to derive from both the suspended floor (Locus 13) and the interior surface of the walls.
Phase XIV: Modern period marked by Bedouin activity and the accumulation of recent debris.

Phase XI: Further collapse post- CE 5th c., possibly the result of the earthquake of CE 512. Major collapses in the Lower Temenos lead to the continued accumulation of fill. At this time the East Colonnade collapses significantly onto a bed of accumulated soil, as does the entablature of the East Exedra.
Phase XIII: Major collapses continue into the Islamic period.
